
'''Book: Jeff Jarvis. What Would Google Do?'''


=Review=

Draft by Tom Rawlings:

"Reading media blogger Jeff Jarvis's book, 'What Would Google Do?' is very interesting and full of great anecdotes, human-level stories and aspirational ideas for technology - but I can't help feeling the book is a little miss-named; it would have been more accurate to call it 'What Would p2p Do?'.  Why?  Because much of the book looks at the contrast of old ways vs. new ways of doing things, it's just the the new ways Jeff describes often have more to do with p2p than Google.  For example take the chapter on banking and insurance entitled, 'Money: Google Capital/First Bank of Google', Jeff talks about peer-leaning and micro-finance as the news ways, of removing the middle-men and connecting people to people for financing.  In the section on insurance he confesses the he didn't think this area could be more 'googley', but on his blog he'd thrown open the topic to the crowd to see what they thought, and the peer-group came back with ideas for new ways of doing insurance - such as peer-insurance. It is also in the media section talking about peer-journalism, in the oft cited (in the book) Craiglist as a means of connecting peers and letting them get on with it.  To be fair, I am still part way though the book and have a bit yet to go, but while I would critique the deeper idea of what Jeff endeavours are uncovering (as in: it's p2p, not Google, that is really emerging) he is an open and enthusiastic writer and I am enjoying his journey."


